\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coulomb Hole Self Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By replacing the electron operators with hole operators in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Inter_Polarization_Eq_1"

\end_inset

, the valence band energy was shifted by a constant value,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{n}(\mathbf{k})\rightarrow E_{n}(\mathbf{k})-\sum_{\mathbf{q}}\Theta_{-\mathbf{q},-\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k}}^{n,n}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

This shift is already implicitly included in the band structure.
 In the high density limit, the Coulomb interaction is screened
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Theta_{s,-\mathbf{q},-\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k}}^{n,n}=\frac{\Theta_{-\mathbf{q},-\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k}}^{n,n}}{\epsilon(\mathbf{q},0)}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the difference between the unscreened and the screened Coulomb interaction
 leads to a density dependent shift
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta E_{CH,n}=\sum_{\mathbf{q}}\Theta_{-\mathbf{q},-\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k}}^{n,n}\left(\frac{1}{\epsilon(\mathbf{q})}-1\right).\label{eq:Coulomb_Hole_Self_Energy}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The shift is denoted as 
\emph on
Debye shift
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
Coulomb-hole self energy
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Screened Exchange Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beside the Coulomb-hole self energy, the transition energy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Transition_Energy"

\end_inset

 is, compared to the free carrier result, reduced by the density dependent
 
\emph on
screened exchange shift
\emph default
,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta E_{SX,mn}(\mathbf{k})=\sum_{\mathbf{q}}\left(\Theta_{\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}^{m,m}n_{m,\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}+\Theta_{\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}^{n,n}n_{n,\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}\right).\label{eq:Screened_Exchange_Shift}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the screened Coulomb potentials are used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, within the screened Hartree-Fock limit, the transition energy
 is therefore renormalized
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hbar\tilde{\omega}_{mn}(\mathbf{k})=\Delta E_{mn}(\mathbf{k})+\Delta E_{CH,n}-\Delta E_{SX,mn}(\mathbf{k}).\label{eq:Band_Gap_Renormalization}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that both contributions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Hole_Self_Energy"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Screened_Exchange_Shift"

\end_inset

 reduce the transition energy and can lead to a significant red shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Solving the Correlated Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to solve the equation of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HF_Polarization_Eq_Motion"

\end_inset

, the collision term is approximated using a decay rate 
\begin_inset Formula $-\gamma p_{mn,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 As equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HF_Polarization_Eq_Motion"

\end_inset

 couples microscopic polarizations 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mn,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 of different 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 values, the equation system has to be solved self-consistently.
 Therefore, the equation is transformed using the same ansatz as in Chapter
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Free_Carriers_Optical_Transitions"

\end_inset

.
 The fast oscillating 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mn,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 is replaced with its slowly-varying envelope
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=p_{mn,\mathbf{k}}e^{-i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)}.\label{eq:Polarization_Slow_Envelope_Def}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inserting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Polarization_Slow_Envelope_Def"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HF_Polarization_Eq_Motion"

\end_inset

, taking the time derivative, using the plane wave expression for the electrical
 field 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Electrical_Field_Ansatz"

\end_inset

, skipping the fast oscillating parts (as they should average out to zero)
 and solving for the steady state leads to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
s_{nm,\mathbf{k}} & = & -\frac{1}{i\left(\tilde{\omega}_{mn}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)+\gamma}\frac{i}{\hbar}\nonumber \\
 &  & \cdot\left\{ \mu_{mn,\mathbf{k}}\frac{E(z)}{2}+\sum\Theta_{\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}s_{nm,\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}\right\} \label{eq:Polarization_Slow_Envelope_Eq}\\
 &  & \cdot\left(n_{m\mathbf{k}}+n_{n\mathbf{k}}-1\right).\nonumber \end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The polarization envelope still depends on the intensity of the considered
 field.
 Therefore, the field independent solution variable is introduced, given
 by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=\frac{2s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}}{E(z)}.\label{eq:Field_Independent_Sol_Var}\end{equation}

\end_inset

In order to obtain a practicable expression, the lineshape and the inversion
 factor are combined into
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=\frac{i}{\hbar}\frac{\left(n_{m\mathbf{k}}+n_{n\mathbf{k}}-1\right)}{i\left(\tilde{\omega}_{mn,\mathbf{k}}-\nu\right)+\gamma}.\label{eq:Lineshape_Inversion_Factor}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inserting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Field_Independent_Sol_Var"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Lineshape_Inversion_Factor"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Polarization_Slow_Envelope_Eq"

\end_inset

, yields
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\sum\Theta_{\mathbf{q},\mathbf{k},\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}+\mathbf{q}}+\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=-\mu_{mn,\mathbf{k}}\Lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation is the self-consistency equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Once solved, the optical susceptibility is calculated using
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi(\nu)=\frac{1}{n_{b}^{2}\epsilon_{0}}\frac{P(z)}{E(z)}=\frac{1}{n_{b}^{2}\epsilon_{0}}\frac{1}{V}\sum_{n,m,\mathbf{k}}\mu_{mn,\mathbf{k}}^{*}\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}.\label{eq:HF_Susceptability}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Absorption, refractive index change and spontaneous emission can therefrom
 be calculated as already presented in the preceding Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Free_Carriers_Optical_Transitions"

\end_inset

.
 In the next section we present the numerical implementation details of
 the solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation Considerations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a consequence of the collisions between particles in the assumed equalibrium
 state, we consider the conduction band and the valence band as two carriers
 reservoirs with Fermi-Dirac distributions for the electrons and holes.
 Thus, we only need to solve the equation of motion for the polarization
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the decay model for the microscopic polarization we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=-i\tilde{\omega}_{mn}(\mathbf{k})p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}-i\Omega_{\mathbf{k}}(z,t)\left(f_{e\mathbf{k}}^{n}+f_{h\mathbf{k}}^{m}-1\right)-\gamma p_{nm,\mathbf{k}},\label{eq:HF_Polarization_Eq_Motion_Numerics}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 denote the conduction and valence subbands, respectvely, involved in the
 transition.
 As for the free carrier model, the electron and hole densities are given
 as input parameters, and the chemical potentials, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{Fc}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{Fv}$
\end_inset

, are calculated as described in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Carrier_Statistics"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the first step for the calculation, the dielectric function 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon(\mathbf{q})$
\end_inset

, the Coulomb-hole self energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{CH,n}$
\end_inset

 and the screened exchange shift energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{SX,mn}(\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 must be evaluated.
 Here we elaborate on the practical numerics for the calculation of these
 terms (and others), and illustrate the results for a 
\begin_inset Formula $200\,\AA$
\end_inset

 wide 
\begin_inset Formula $GaAs$
\end_inset

 well, surrounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $Ga_{0.9}Al_{0.1}As$
\end_inset

 barriers with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-doped layers introduced at 
\begin_inset Formula $1000\,\AA$
\end_inset

 away from the barrier-well boundaries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is more convinient to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $q\epsilon(\mathbf{q})$
\end_inset

 than only 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon(\mathbf{q})$
\end_inset

.
 With Fermi-Dirac electron and hole distributions, we have from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Full_Lindhards_Eq"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
q\epsilon(\mathbf{q})=q-\frac{e^{2}}{2\epsilon_{r}A}\sum_{n\mathbf{k}}\frac{f_{n,\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{q}}-f_{n,\mathbf{k}}}{E_{n}(\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{q})-E_{n}(\mathbf{k})}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Converting the sum over the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

-states into an integral, adding the sum over the spin, choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 as the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 and assuming no angular dependence for the subband structure, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
q\epsilon(q)=q-\frac{e^{2}}{4\pi^{2}\epsilon_{r}}\sum_{n}\int_{0}^{\infty}dk\, k\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\theta\frac{f_{n,\left|\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{q}\right|}-f_{n,\mathbf{\left|k\right|}}}{E_{n}\left(\left|\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{q}\right|\right)-E_{n}(\mathbf{\left|k\right|})}.\label{eq:Epsilon_q_Numeric}\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left|\mathbf{k}'\right|=\left|\mathbf{k}-\mathbf{q}\right|=\left(k^{2}+q^{2}-2kq\cos\theta\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The integrals can be eveluated here, as before, using the trapezoidal method
 for integration.
 
