.
 The last difficulty resides in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\mathbf{k}}(z,t)$
\end_inset

.
 The first step is to eliminate the rapidly varying phase factor from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and to work with 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Polarization_Slow_Envelope_Eq"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\frac{d}{dt}s_{nm,\mathbf{k}} & = & -\left(i\left(\tilde{\omega}_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)+\gamma\right)s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}-\frac{i}{\hbar}\mu_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{E(z)}{2}w_{\mathbf{k}}\nonumber \\
 &  & -\frac{i}{\hbar}w_{\mathbf{k}}\sum_{\mathbf{k}\neq\mathbf{k}'}\Theta_{s,\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}s_{nm,\mathbf{k}'},\label{eq:HF_Slow_Polarization_Eq_Motion_Numerics}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\mathbf{k}}=f_{e\mathbf{k}}^{n}+f_{h\mathbf{k}}^{m}-1$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain suscptability spectrum of a medium, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HF_Slow_Polarization_Eq_Motion_Numerics"

\end_inset

 is solved for the steady state (as in the previous section), which leads
 to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=-\frac{i}{\hbar}\frac{w_{\mathbf{k}}\mu_{\mathbf{k}}}{i\left(\tilde{\omega}_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)+\gamma}\left(\frac{E(z)}{2}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathbf{k}}}\sum_{\mathbf{k}\neq\mathbf{k}'}\Theta_{s,\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}s_{nm,\mathbf{k}'}\right).\label{eq:Steady_State_Sol_Polarization}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We define two new variables, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

-dependent complex susceptability function 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\chi_{\mathbf{k}}^{0}=-\Lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\mu_{\mathbf{k}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the Coulomb enhancement factor
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}=\frac{\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}}{\chi_{\mathbf{k}}^{0}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 where defined in the previous section.
 Substituting these two expressions into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Steady_State_Sol_Polarization"

\end_inset

 we obtian
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}(\nu)=1+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathbf{k}}}\sum_{\mathbf{k}\neq\mathbf{k}'}\Theta_{s,\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}\chi_{\mathbf{k}'}^{0}\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}'}^{n,m}(\nu).\label{eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_1}\end{equation}

\end_inset

We consider the last part of this equation and transfor the sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}'$
\end_inset

 into an integral as before.
 Furthermore, we assume that the microscopic polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}$
\end_inset

 has no angular dependence
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathbf{k}}}\sum_{\mathbf{k}\neq\mathbf{k}'}\Theta_{s,\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}\chi_{\mathbf{k}'}^{0}\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}'}^{n,m}(\nu)=\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathbf{k}}}\int_{0}^{\infty}dk'\,\varepsilon_{k,k'}\chi_{k'}^{0}\Gamma_{k'}^{n,m}(\nu),\label{eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Part}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{k,k'}=\frac{e^{2}}{2\pi^{2}\epsilon_{r}}k'\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\theta'\frac{G_{\mathbf{q}}^{n,m}}{q\epsilon(q)}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inserting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Part"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_1"

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{k}^{n,m}(\nu)=1+\frac{1}{\mu_{k}}\int_{0}^{\infty}dk'\,\varepsilon_{k,k'}\chi_{k'}^{0}\Gamma_{k'}^{n,m}(\nu).\label{eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Various approaches exist in the literature to solve this self-consistent
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Haug2009,Chow1994"

\end_inset

.
 We choose to use the most general matrix inversion method, in-spite of
 its tendency to be rater resource consuming, as apposed to various approximate
 methods (such as Pade and the dominant momentum methods).
 To this end we approximate the integral over the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 space by a sum of trapezoidal areas and discretize 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k'$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 values and constant step size 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An elternative choise for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta k$
\end_inset

 is to take the elements of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 vector as the support of a Gaussian qudrature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_2"

\end_inset

 can thus be written in a matrix form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{M}\cdot\mathbf{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}=\mathbf{1},\label{eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_3}\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}=\left(\Gamma_{k_{1}}^{n,m},\Gamma_{k_{2}}^{n,m},\cdots,\Gamma_{k_{n}}^{n,m}\right)^{T}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{M}=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1-\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{1}}}\varepsilon_{k_{1},k_{1}'}\chi_{k_{1}'}^{0} & -\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{1}}}\varepsilon_{k_{1},k_{2}'}\chi_{k_{2}'}^{0} & \cdots & -\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{1}}}\varepsilon_{k_{1},k_{n}'}\chi_{k_{n}'}^{0}\\
-\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{1}}}\varepsilon_{k_{1},k_{1}'}\chi_{k_{1}'}^{0} & 1-\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{2}}}\varepsilon_{k_{2},k_{2}'}\chi_{k_{2}'}^{0} & \cdots & -\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{2}}}\varepsilon_{k_{2},k_{n}'}\chi_{k_{n}'}^{0}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
-\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{n}}}\varepsilon_{k_{n},k_{1}'}\chi_{k_{1}'}^{0} & -\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{n}}}\varepsilon_{k_{n},k_{2}'}\chi_{k_{2}'}^{0} & \cdots & 1-\frac{\Delta_{k}}{\mu_{k_{n}}}\varepsilon_{k_{n},k_{n}'}\chi_{k_{n}'}^{0}\end{array}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_3"

\end_inset

 can now be solved using standard mathematical methods to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}$
\end_inset

.
 The microscopic polarization can be obtain using 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p_{nm,\mathbf{k}}=\frac{1}{2}e^{-i\left(k_{0}z-\nu t-\phi(z)\right)}E(z)\chi_{k}^{0}\Gamma_{k}^{n,m}.\label{eq:HF_Final_Polarization}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Insering 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HF_Final_Polarization"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HF_Susceptability"

\end_inset

 and using the definitions in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Free_Carriers_Optical_Transitions"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Intensity_Gain"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Sp_Emission_Definition"

\end_inset

, we can write the expressions for the absorption (or the gain amplitude)
 and spontanious emission spectra
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\alpha_{HF}(\nu) & = & -\Im\left\{ \frac{i\nu}{\hbar c\epsilon_{0}n_{b}\pi\mathcal{L}}\sum_{n,m,\mathbf{k}}\left|\mu_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right|^{2}\frac{w_{\mathbf{k}}}{i\left(\tilde{\omega}_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)+\gamma}\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}(\nu)\right\} \nonumber \\
 & = & -\Im\left\{ \frac{i\nu}{\hbar c\epsilon_{0}n_{b}\pi\mathcal{L}}\sum_{n,m}\int_{0}^{\infty}dk\, k\left|\mu_{nm,\mathbf{k}}\right|^{2}\frac{w_{k}}{i\left(\tilde{\omega}_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})-\nu\right)+\gamma}\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}(\nu)\right\} \label{eq:HF_Absorption}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r_{sp,HF}(\nu)=-\frac{n_{b}^{2}(\hbar\nu)^{2}}{\pi^{2}\hbar^{3}c^{2}}\frac{1}{1-\exp\left(\left(\hbar\nu-\left(E_{Fc}-E_{Fv}\right)\right)/k_{B}T\right)}\alpha_{HF}(\nu),\label{eq:HF_Sp_Emission}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{\mathbf{k}}^{n,m}(\nu)$
\end_inset

 are the solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Coulomb_Enhancement_Factor_3"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\omega}_{n,m}(\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

 is the renormalized bandgap defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Band_Gap_Renormalization"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the length if the 2D quantum structure.
 
\end_layout

