\begin_layout Section
Beyond the Hartree-Fock Approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the previous section we presented the screened Hartree-Fock approximation
 and its consequences for the absorption spectra.
 It represents a simple model which accounts for the plasma screening but
 not for the particle collisions.
 As a next level of cpmplication, next higher level of approximations can
 be computed referred to as Coulomb correlations.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Excitonic-Effects"

\end_inset

Excitonic States 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bandstructure and optical properties of semiconductors we have discussed
 in chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:Electronic_Properties_Semiconductors"

\end_inset

 are based on the assumption that the valence band is filled with electrons
 and the conduction band is empty.
 The effect of the electrons in the conduction band and holes in the valence
 band is only manifested through the occupation probabilities without altering
 the bandstructure.
 In reality, of course, there is a Coulombic interaction between an electron
 and another electron or hole.
 Earlier in this chapter we have outlined a simple but rigorous many-body
 model for this interaction.
 However, there is one important problem, that of excitonic effects in semicondu
ctors, that can be addressed by simpler theoretical techniques.
 In this section we explore the basic model for the excitonic states in
 semiconductors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electron-hole pair forms a bound state which is described by an envelope
 function.
 The form if the envelope function describing the bound state can be calculated
 using the Coulombic interaction as a perturbation.
 Two important classes of excitons exist depending upon the extent of the
 periodic envelope function as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Excitons_Schematic"

\end_inset

.
 When the envelope function is confined to just a few unit cells, the excitons
 are classified as Frenkel excitons.
 Due to their restricted spatial extent, the Heisenberg uncertainty principle
 indicates that their treatment necessitates dealing with the full bandstructure
 of the semiconductor.
 On the other hand, if the envelope function extends over several hundred
 Angstroms, near bandedge electron and hole states can be used to describe
 them.
 Such excitons are called Mott or Wannier excitons and responsible for the
 excitonic physics in semiconductors.
 
