\begin_layout Standard
Now we consider the low-excitation regime of the semiconductor, where an
 extremely small density of electrons and holes exist.
 We therefore concentrate on the analysis of one-electron-hole pair effects.
 The effective mass theory can be used to describe these excitons and accordingl
y the problem is presented by the following equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
-\left[\frac{\hbar^{2}\nabla_{\mathbf{r}}^{2}}{2m_{r}}+V(r)\right]\psi_{l}(\mathbf{r})=E_{l}\psi_{l}(\mathbf{r}),\label{eq:Wannier_Eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V(r)$
\end_inset

 is the Coulomb interaction potential, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{m_{r}}=\frac{1}{m_{e}^{*}}-\frac{1}{m_{h}^{*}}\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the inverse reduced mass and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=\mathbf{r}_{e}-\mathbf{r}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the relative location of the two particles.
 This equation has exactly the form of a two-particle 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Schr
\backslash
"{o}dinger 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equation for the relative motion of an electron and a hole interacting
 via the attractive Coulomb potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(r)$
\end_inset

, and it is called the 
\emph on
Wannier equation
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

.
 This equation have been derived under the assumption that the Coulomb potential
 varies little within one unit cell.
 This assumption is valid only if the resulting electron–hole–pair Bohr
 radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 which determines the extension of the ground state wave function is considerabl
y larger than a lattice constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now discuss the bound-state solutions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Wannier_Eq"

\end_inset

.
 For the sake of mathematical ease we transform the Wannier equation to
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(-\nabla_{\rho}^{2}-\frac{\lambda}{\rho}\right)\psi(\rho)=\frac{2m_{r}E_{l}}{\hbar^{2}\alpha^{2}}\psi(\rho),\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we introduced the scaled radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=r\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 We also define the following two parameters 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{e^{2}2m_{r}}{\epsilon_{0}\hbar^{2}\alpha}=2\frac{1}{\alpha a_{0}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{0}=\frac{\hbar^{2}\epsilon_{0}}{e^{2}m_{r}}.\label{eq:Exciton_Rydberg_Radius}\end{equation}

\end_inset

As in the hydrogen-atom case, the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{l}$
\end_inset

 is negative for bound states (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{bound}<E_{g}$
\end_inset

) and positive for the ionization continuum.
 We define
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{0}^{2}\alpha^{2}=-\frac{8m_{r}E_{l}a_{0}^{2}}{\hbar^{2}}=-4\frac{E_{l}}{E_{0}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the energy unit 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{0}=\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{r}a_{0}^{2}}.\label{eq:Exciton_Rydberg_Energy}\end{equation}

\end_inset

to rewrite the Wannier equation as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(-\nabla_{\rho}^{2}-\frac{\lambda}{\rho}\right)\psi(\rho)=-\frac{1}{4}\psi(\rho),\label{eq:Reduced_Wannier_Eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{e^{2}}{\epsilon_{0}\hbar}\sqrt{-\frac{m_{r}}{2E_{l}}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

With this choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}$
\end_inset

 the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 will be real for bound states and imaginary for the ionization continuum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Reduced_Wannier_Eq"

\end_inset

 for the two-dimensional case, we use the following cylindrical ansatz 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi(\rho)=f_{l}(\rho)\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{il\phi},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Laplace equation for the radial part is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\frac{1}{\rho}\frac{\partial}{\partial\rho}\rho\frac{\partial}{\partial\rho}+\frac{\lambda}{\rho}-\frac{1}{4}-\frac{m^{2}}{\rho^{2}}\right)f_{l}(\rho)=0.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The eigenfunctions of this equation can we written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f_{l}(\rho)=\rho^{\left|l\right|}e^{-\frac{\rho}{2}}R(\rho),\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R(\rho)=\sum_{\iota}\beta_{\iota}\rho^{\iota}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Terminating the series for certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota=\iota_{max}$
\end_inset

, so that all 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{\iota\geq\iota_{max}}=0$
\end_inset

, we can define the main quantum number as 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{max}+\left|l\right|+\frac{1}{2}=\lambda\equiv n+\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1,\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 Using standard partial differential equations methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset

, this eigenvalues of the problem can be obtained to be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{n}=-E_{0}\frac{1}{\left(n+1/2\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\mbox{with}\,\,\, n=0,1,\ldots,\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

, defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Exciton_Rydberg_Energy"

\end_inset

, is the exciton Rydberg energy, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

, defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Exciton_Rydberg_Radius"

\end_inset

, is the Rydberg radius.
