\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{q}^{p}$
\end_inset

 are the associated Laguerre polynomials 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\frac{2r}{\left(n+1/2\right)a_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The excitonic wavefunction, derived thus far, can be formulated in the following
 alternative form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi\left(\mathbf{r}\right)=\varphi_{n}\left(\mathbf{r}\right)\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Omega}}e^{i\mathbf{K}\cdot\mathbf{R}},\label{eq:Excitonic_WF_COM}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the center of mass coordinate is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}=\left(m_{e}\mathbf{r}_{e}+m_{h}\mathbf{r}_{h}\right)/M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M=m_{e}+m_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{K}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the center-of-mass momentum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although an exciton has a similar internal structure to a hydrogen atom,
 a Wannier exciton has much larger Bohr radius and much smaller binding
 energy than a hydrogen atom, owing to the small effective mass of electrons
 and the large dielectric constant in semiconductors.
 For instance, in the ground (
\begin_inset Formula $1s$
\end_inset

) state, the electron and hole in a Wannier exciton are much more loosely
 bound than the electron and proton in a hydrogen atom.
 On the other hand, since the exciton's wavefunction is extended over many
 lattice sites of the crystal, the exciton collects the dipole oscillator
 strength of many atoms.
\end_layout

