\begin_layout Subsection
Exciton Optical Spectra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
With the knowledge of the exciton wavefunctions and energy eigenvalues,
 the inhomogenous eqaution 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Polarization_Eq_Motion_Unexcited_Crystal_2"

\end_inset

 can be solved, and the optical spectrum of the semiconductor can be obtained.
 We limit our treatment to the discussion of optically allowed transitions
 in direct-gap semiconductors, which are relevant for this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As a first step, we expand the microscopic polarization into the solutions
 of the Wannier eqaution
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p_{eh}(\mathbf{r},\nu)=\sum_{l}b_{l}\psi_{l}(\mathbf{r}).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inserting this expansion into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Polarization_Eq_Motion_Unexcited_Crystal_2"

\end_inset

, multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}^{*}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 and integrating over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{l}b_{l}\left[\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{l}\right]\int_{\Omega}d^{3}\mathbf{r}\,\psi_{\mu}^{*}(\mathbf{r})\psi_{l}(\mathbf{r})=-\mu_{eh}E(\nu)\Omega\psi_{m}^{*}(\mathbf{r}=0),\end{equation}

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{m}=-\frac{\mu_{eh}\Omega\psi_{m}^{*}(\mathbf{r}=0)}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{l}}E(\nu).\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus we can write the microscopic polarization in the Fourier space as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p_{eh,\mathbf{k}}(\nu)=-\sum_{\mathbf{k}}E(\nu)\frac{\mu_{eh}\psi_{m}^{*}(\mathbf{r}=0)}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{l}}\int_{\Omega}d^{3}\mathbf{r}\,\psi_{l}(\mathbf{r})e^{i\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The total polarization can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
P(\nu) & = & -2\Omega\sum_{l}\left|\mu_{eh}\right|^{2}\left|\psi_{l}(\mathbf{r}=0)\right|^{2}E(\nu)\nonumber \\
 &  & \cdot\left[\frac{1}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{l}}-\frac{1}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)+E_{g}+E_{l}}\right],\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the factor 2 comes from the spin summation implicitly included the
 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset


\series default
-summation.
 The susceptability of the electron-hole-pair is obtained as before to be
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\chi(\nu) & = & -2\left|\mu_{eh}\right|^{2}\sum_{m}\left|\psi_{m}(\mathbf{r}=0)\right|^{2}\nonumber \\
 &  & \cdot\left[\frac{1}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{m}}-\frac{1}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)+E_{g}+E_{m}}\right].\label{eq:E_H_Pair_Susceptability}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The first term in is the resonant contribution and the second term is the
 nonresonant part, respectively.
 One often leaves out the nonresonant part since it does not contribute
 to the absorption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the 2D case 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:E_H_Pair_Susceptability"

\end_inset

 can be simplified to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Haug2009"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\chi(\nu) & = & -\frac{\left|\mu_{eh}\right|^{2}}{\mathcal{L}\pi a_{0}^{2}E_{0}}\left[\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{2}{\left(n+1/2\right)^{3}}\frac{E_{0}}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{n}}\right.\nonumber \\
 &  & \left.+\int dx\,\frac{xe^{\pi/x}}{\cosh(\pi/x)}\frac{E_{0}}{\hbar\left(\nu+i\delta\right)-E_{g}-E_{0}x^{2}}\right],\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and the resulting absorption spectrum is given by the 
\emph on
Elliot formula
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha(\nu)=\alpha_{0}^{2D}\frac{\hbar\nu}{E_{0}}\left[\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{4}{\left(n+1/2\right)^{3}}\delta\left(\Delta+\frac{1}{\left(n+1/2\right)^{2}}\right)+\Theta(\Delta)\frac{e^{\pi/\sqrt{\Delta}}}{\cosh\left(e^{\pi/\sqrt{\Delta}}\right)}\right].\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\alpha_{0}^{2D}=\frac{4\pi^{2}}{\hbar n_{b}c}\left|\mu_{eh}\right|^{2}\frac{1}{(2\pi a_{0})^{2}}\mathcal{A}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The term 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
C(\nu)=\frac{e^{\pi/\sqrt{\Delta}}}{\cosh\left(e^{\pi/\sqrt{\Delta}}\right)}\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the Coulomb enhancement factor, which shows that the attractive Coulomb
 interaction not only creates the bound states but has also a pronounced
 influence on the ionization continuum compared to the free carrier case.
 
